    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3787731207" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3787731207" />
    <a title="Beenish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/106139933-beenish"><img alt="Beenish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616760756p2/106139933.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3787731207?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beenish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beenish" href="/user/show/106139933-beenish">Beenish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3787731207" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15885238958580183701"><b>2★ | because a book with Nikolai in it deserves to be rated.</b>—<i>otherwise this book gets 0 stars from me.</i><br/><br/><blockquote>
  <i>
    <b>We do our best. We try. And usually, it makes no difference at all.</b>
  </i>
</blockquote><br/><br/>This book also deserves a rating coz I read it when I was feeling very low and so many lines made me feel relatable and better. For example, the line I quoted above.<br/><br/>Now, coming back to the <b>book talk</b>,<br/>Does the plot get better? No.<br/>Does the protagonist get better? No.<br/>Does the love interest get better? No.<br/>Does the villain </span>
  <span id="freeText15885238958580183701" style="display:none"><b>2★ | because a book with Nikolai in it deserves to be rated.</b>—<i>otherwise this book gets 0 stars from me.</i><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>
    <b>We do our best. We try. And usually, it makes no difference at all.</b>
  </i>
</blockquote><br><br>This book also deserves a rating coz I read it when I was feeling very low and so many lines made me feel relatable and better. For example, the line I quoted above.<br><br>Now, coming back to the <b>book talk</b>,<br>Does the plot get better? No.<br>Does the protagonist get better? No.<br>Does the love interest get better? No.<br>Does the villain get better? Slightly, yes.<br>Does anyone (esp. Mal) die? No.<br>BUT,<br>Does the author create a new character that becomes the life blown into this book like a soul to the body? <b>YES!</b><br>Does anyone have a Character? Nikolai.<br>Does Nikolai have a personality? The best!<br>Does anyone have a sense of humour? Nikolai.<br>Does Nikolai become my new favourite character? Yes, from the moment I met him and didn't even know his name.<br><br><b>I am so not bothered about telling you the ridiculous plot that made me wanna cry for reading it. And I'm not exaggerating. So if you're interested in my rant, WELCOME.</b><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“If you want to lie to me, go ahead. But I’m not going to pretend to believe you.”<br>“Why not?” asked Sturmhond, stepping into the tent. “It’s only common courtesy.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>I mean, seriously? XD I LOVED Sturmhond ❤️<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“You heard Prince Perfect,” Mal said, and joined us at the table.<br>Nikolai grinned. “I’ve had a lot of nicknames, but that one is easily the most accurate.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>And, I Love Nikolai 🤣<br>AND, for this rare moment, I loved Mal for calling him Prince Perfect.<br>And I hated him for saying something right, lol.<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“I wanted to make you human,” he said. “All they see when they look at you is the Sun Summoner. They see a threat, another powerful Grisha like the Darkling. I want them to see a daughter or a sister or a friend. I want them to see Alina.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Just listen okay? I STILL hate him a lot. I mean, I could burn with the hate I have for him. But the author tried REALLY HARD to make us see he's a human. To make us see he's better than he's been acting around. And as much as I appreciate a man saying things that Mal says, I think they just don't suit him. It feels so fake. Like he wants to be loved but I'm sorry, I want him to <b>DIE!</b><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“Why are you so ready to attack him?”<br>“Why are you so quick to defend him?”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Um okay. AND every time he DOES say something nice, he does something worse to erase that good he does/says.<br>I DO NOT CARE about a man who is Mal. Who is so jealous and insecure and possessive and bossy and acts like he's THE MAN but isn't really.<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“I want to kiss you,” he said.<br>“You already kissed me,” I replied with a nervous laugh.<br>A smile tugged at his lips. “I want to kiss you again,” he amended.</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Isn't he just the BEST MAN ALIVE?<br>Mal is a very boring and dry pussy.<br>The Darkling is very hot but just randomly grabs and kisses and manipulates you.<br>But <b>Nikolai has the guts and courtesy to tell you he wants to kiss you when he knows you have a boyfriend and doesn't force you or take advantage of you and keeps control on his desire.</b><br>Now, THAT'S the man I want.<br>I would say Alina is stupid to reject Nikolai and choose Mal.<br>I mean, even animals have brains imo.<br>But at the same time, I'm so happy she doesn't say yes coz I LOVE NIKOLAI and deeply feel he deserves a much, much better person than her.<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“At least she doesn’t flinch when I touch her,” he spat. “You don’t want me, so why do you care if she does?”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>You motherfucking asshole! You don't even deserve the right to be in this god damned book! Be grateful you're here and NOT dead and that we READERS are tolerating you!<br><b>I wish I could strangle this guy!!!</b><br><br><br>In the end, all I want to say is that going through this book felt like a waste except, I'm very glad I met Nikolai. For some he might be just another guy who lightens up the mood but for me, he's everything that kept this book alive.<br>I liked his way of flirting with Alina. Tbh, I call that decent flirting, lol.<br>And, <b>Ah! The Darkling.</b><br>I loved him and started disliking him and hated him and then I started liking him again. The thing is, he is the villain and a very good one at that. But my desire to know the boy and how he became the villain wasn't fulfilled. That was very disappointing. Like verrrrrryyyy disappointing. 😔<br><b>Baghra, Genya, Zoya, David, Nikolai.</b> They were 1000x better than the main characters, Alina and Mal.<br>They're both very bland.<br>Very stupid.<br>And the idiots deserve to live together.<br><br><br><b>my reviews of</b><br><a href="https://bit.ly/3pcVX37" rel="nofollow noopener">The Demon in the Wood</a> 4★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/3jM5Cwm" rel="nofollow noopener">The Witch of Duva</a> 5★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/2OoBQC7" rel="nofollow noopener">Shadow and Bone</a> 3★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/37b2WDs" rel="nofollow noopener">The Tailor</a> 4★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/2NowTIW" rel="nofollow noopener">Little Knife</a> 5★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/2N3d9uD" rel="nofollow noopener">The Too-Clever Fox</a> 4★<br><a href="https://bit.ly/3rTheQP" rel="nofollow noopener">Ruin and Rising</a> 2.5★<br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3824143744" rel="nofollow noopener">Six of Crows</a> 4★<br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3141343990" rel="nofollow noopener">Crooked Kindgom</a> 4.5★<br><br>_____________________<br><br><b>
  <u>pre-read review</u>
</b><br><br><b>1.5 ★ for Nikolai</b> and point 5 for a really quick read.<br><br>I can't believe this book is so loved. Honestly, this book deserves 0★ I just, I can'ttt.. If you see my rating, know that it is only for Nikolai! The boy who is aka the <b>the life the author blew into this book</b><br>_____________________<br><br>Edit: SCRATCH everything I wrote before/below. Okay not everything. Just add this:<br><br><b>Nikolai OWNS this book!!!</b><br>EVERY PAGE he has a dialogue on, it shines! I'm telling you, it shines!! ✨😅<br>_____________________<br><br>So—Am I up for another book with the same old Protagonist aka. <b>The aMaZiNg Alina</b>? *eye roll*<br>—Do I want to see Alina and Mal being all lovey-dovey? *eye roll* ugh.<br>—Do I think this would get better? Obviously NO. How can it when it's written in first person through the pov of a very stupid girl?<br><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1612756137i/30830346._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>—oh look, <b>Sarah J. Maas</b>, the great great author liked Shadow and Bone and her Acotar book is obviously a very bad book written on the same plotting style as this book, (<i>because this WAS better than THAT and yet not good at all</i>) so like, idk. It shows me I can't take Sjm's word on anything. I'm <b>officially her critic</b> and will never be on good terms with her.<br><b>ANYWAYS</b><br><br>—the Darkling? Naaaa. Not a fan. I just started loving him (<i>and still do</i>) for that interesting shadow power he has and how good he looks and because of that fanart from Morgana0anagrom ofc. But idk. There's nothing more to him then him being the villain after that "plot twist" *eye roll* jk. It did shock me. :/ Lilah called him a Disney villain and thats just how I can see him now. <br>*Eye roll*<br>*Eye roll*<br>*Eye roll*<br>—cont. <br>I hope I don't lose my eyes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15885238958580183701" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

